Doing an aggressive scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.38.72 -p 80 against port 80 returns the result above. I obtained useful information such as the framework used to create the web application. And the webpage seems to be a login page.


Before enumerating the web application on port 80, I will download the task files on my machine. It consists of two files: usernames.txt and passwords.txt. I removed the .txt from both file names to make it easier to run hydra. Time to begin enumeration now. Both of these files contains hundreds of entries to perform the bruteforce attack.

Enumeration & Exploitation

Port 80: HTTP

The login webpage above is displayed to me after visiting this web application via a web-browser. I can attempt to bruteforce, but the task mentions a rate limiter is in place. I will need to find out more about this rate limiter first.


The source-code of the webpage contains the useful information above. By the looks of it, there is CAPTCHA too according to the source-code? Therefore, bruteforcing using hydra will not work. I will need to create a script to automate this bruteforce attack while also handling the rate limiter in place.


I created the first version of the script above to make a request to the target machine's web application. This script also reads in the usernames file and prints each entry to the screen. This script worked successfully.


The second version of the script is shown above. This script is responsible for making a POST request to the target machine by using the usernames. It is also responsible for detecting if the web application's captcha security mechanism is turned on or not -- if too many POST requests are sent.


The final script is shown above to find the valid usernames. It uses regular expression to find the CAPTCHA question in the HTML page. Then this is solved using the eval function in Python. Since the string does not exist is displayed when invalid usernames are entered, I used this same string to filter the wrong and correct usernames. I tried Error: The user first and it did not work.


And bingo! After running the script, the username natalie is valid as shown above. Time to bruteforce the password of this user now.


I modified the previous script to create the final script above to bruteforce the password of user natalie. Again, it just sends the username natalie and the CAPTCHA. After doing this, it uses Invalid password for string to filter out correct & incorrect passwords during the login.


Now I have the password sk8board belonging to the user natalie. I can use the username and password to gain access to the web application on port 80 to obtain the flag. GG.
